Soul of corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he not drive.
He asked me why.
“You have drunk,” I said to him, “haven’t you been afraid of the police?”
Boris replied to me: 'No, I have a document in the likeness of Benjamin Franklin, it always serves as a service.'
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped beside it.
Obviously, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would meet a police officer who was not corrupt.
'Impossible', declared Boris, 'to enter the traffic police department, you must buy the silence of your chief.'
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy the silence of your chief?
The half of Moscow drivers use illegally bought driving licenses.
Idiots who try to do things by the book drown in bureaucratic red tape.
Paying 100 dollars, you can drive in the city without brakes! »
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels that we see today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom one doesn't offer them, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or abandonment.
Police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one anywhere is immunized.
Recently, I was visiting a village of dachas in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxurious but similar place to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and tastefully decorated houses, I asked who owned them, and I heard that one belonged to an assistant to the Moscow mayor, another to a famous singer, another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
The most attractive property belonged to a modest tax inspector.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it had not been led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police officers who sell arms and supplies to the rebels.
The Russian television recently showed a bus running a shuttle service from Grozny to Moscow, the same bus that brought the 120 kilograms of explosives used for the siege of the Dubrovka theater, where so many victims perished during the assault intended to liberate the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from smelling them.
A very unnecessary precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver who didn't know what he was transporting said he was arrested 50 times along his route, and always for the same thing.
A policeman came and asked him: "do you know the price?", and the driver replied: "of course, I know it", paying the bribe before leaving.
Without bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, so entire days for the trip.
The war in Chechnya continues indefinitely not only because the Chechen rebels have for allies Al Qaeda and all the 'international terrorism' but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, the civilians who accept bribes and the thieves, who first tax the Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell arms and explosives to the terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are and provide the rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used arms bought from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern arms.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no armorer's shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have their own ammunition stocks, from which the arms are stolen and sold.
And not only arms: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
The Russian corruption reaches catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more harshly?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more it will be necessary to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those who are called "simple people" view this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say about their mayor "yes of course, he steals, but look at everything he has done for the city!"
Ordinary people don't like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother told me one day that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller stopped her, telling her that passengers with a ticket were not admitted to the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an officer and he will cross your son's name off the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter into any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can take the wheel while drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Benjamin Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When Emperor Peter, disgusted by the corruption of Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects".
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has deteriorated.
Removing corruption might as well leave the state without citizens, but if we don't stop the progress of corruption, the citizens will soon be left without a state.
